374
00:32:53,080 --> 00:32:56,920
and you have a reasonable sample size. Let's 
say you've got 10 people and four of them said  

375
00:32:56,920 --> 00:33:00,920
they'd be very disappointed without it, you're 
still going to get something useful from those  

376
00:33:00,920 --> 00:33:07,200
four. But I wouldn't say that's a sample size 
that you can really go to market on, so yeah.

377
00:33:07,200 --> 00:33:09,040
What's a good sample size 
you look for of just, "Okay,  

378
00:33:09,040 --> 00:33:11,080
this is actually good data I want to rely on?"

379
00:33:11,080 --> 00:33:17,280
It's really funny. So much of the stuff I 
self-learned, but I basically at one point said  

380
00:33:17,280 --> 00:33:22,840
I need at least 30 responses, and I just thought 
I randomly made up a number and then I had people  

381
00:33:22,840 --> 00:33:28,000
telling me, "Yeah, 30 is the minimum that you want 
on stuff." Okay. And even when I first created  

382
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:36,080
this survey, I remember showing it to the 
co-founder of SlideShare and her PhD was in  

383
00:33:36,080 --> 00:33:41,480
survey-related stuff like cognitive psychology, 
but she basically said it was really about  

384
00:33:41,480 --> 00:33:46,160
surveying. And she's like, "This methodology 
is amazing. How did you come up with this?"  

385
00:33:46,160 --> 00:33:51,240
And so having some of that validation around 
these things helped. But a lot of it was just,  

386
00:33:51,240 --> 00:33:58,080
again, driven by my own curiosity and also 
just knowing that that failure is such a  

387
00:33:58,080 --> 00:34:05,760
likely outcome that trying to reverse engineer 
that failure, and then the number one reason  

388
00:34:05,760 --> 00:34:10,280
for failure would be that people don't actually 
care about the product. And so when I find that,  

389
00:34:10,280 --> 00:34:15,520
that's a really good sign that we're 
now down to an execution challenge.

390
00:34:15,520 --> 00:34:21,600
And there's this obvious element of you 
may have product-market fit with people,  

391
00:34:21,600 --> 00:34:25,240
but that group might end up being very small 
and the business you build around it could  

392
00:34:25,240 --> 00:34:28,760
actually be cool, but it's not going to be a 
massive business. Is there anything there you  

393
00:34:28,760 --> 00:34:35,160
can share? It's hard to know the size opportunity 
even though some people really, really like it.

394
00:34:35,160 --> 00:34:43,240
Yeah, I talked about I go to a multiple choice 
after I initially use open-ended questions to  

395
00:34:43,960 --> 00:34:48,360
crowdsource the different use cases. But 
then I try to force people in a bucket,  

396
00:34:48,360 --> 00:34:51,320
and then I can run filters on each of 
those buckets and I'll be like, "Oh,  

397
00:34:51,320 --> 00:34:57,360
people who use it this way are like 60% likely 
to be very disappointed without the product,  

398
00:34:57,360 --> 00:35:01,640
but people who use it this way are 
35% likely to be very disappointed,  

399
00:35:01,640 --> 00:35:09,800
but way more people use it the 35% way." 
And so then, do you want that intensely  

400
00:35:09,800 --> 00:35:17,200
loyal group or the much broader group 
that's maybe a bit less, but almost there? 

401
00:35:17,200 --> 00:35:24,960
I think that becomes a bit of a strategic 
conversation of do we want to have a better  

402
00:35:24,960 --> 00:35:31,800
chance of surviving, going after a niche that 
we know we can serve well? Or have we raised so  

403
00:35:31,800 --> 00:35:38,800
much money that we have to go after a really big 
market, and one that's not going to be long-term?  

404
00:35:38,800 --> 00:35:43,640
But maybe then you're like, "Okay, once I have 
traction in that market, I can start to try  

405
00:35:43,640 --> 00:35:48,040
to appeal to some other markets." But I think 
that's where some strategic decisions come in.

406
00:35:48,040 --> 00:35:50,160
Do you have a heuristic of 
which you often recommend  

407
00:35:50,160 --> 00:35:53,120
or is it very dependent on the situation?

408
00:35:53,120 --> 00:35:59,760
I prefer a more passionate customer base and 
work from there, just because I think your  

409
00:35:59,760 --> 00:36:08,120
biggest competition when you're really innovating 
is just being irrelevant. And so if you're deeply  

410
00:36:08,120 --> 00:36:12,000
relevant to anyone, I think that gives you 
a much better chance of long-term success.

411
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:15,160
Awesome. That's a really good insight. Okay, 
two more questions along this line and then  

412
00:36:15,160 --> 00:36:20,160
I want to talk about growth strategy. One very 
tactical question. Is there a tool you recommend  

413
00:36:20,160 --> 00:36:25,800
for doing this sort of survey? Do you recommend 
inline? In the product? An email? Something else?

414
00:36:25,800 --> 00:36:31,440
I've used a lot of different tools. I actually had 
a survey business that I sold to private equity  

415
00:36:31,440 --> 00:36:47,000
years ago. It is called Qualaroo. That's an inflow 
survey tool. I think just using SurveyMonkey with  

416
00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:56,560
emailed surveys works fine. And for me, it's a lot 
more of what's pleasant for the customer to fill  

417
00:36:56,560 --> 00:37:02,080
out and then what's going to give me something 
where I can work really easily with the data? So  

418
00:37:02,080 --> 00:37:08,760
at Bounce, for example, they had already intercom 
in place that had just introduced surveying,  

419
00:37:08,760 --> 00:37:15,640
but it was a really crappy customer experience, 
at least at that time. That's been almost a year  

420
00:37:15,640 --> 00:37:22,200
now or actually a little over a year. And so 
I'm really sensitive to is it a good survey  

421
00:37:22,200 --> 00:37:30,400
experience for the consumer itself? But yeah, I 
don't think I'm stuck to any one platform there.

422
00:37:30,400 --> 00:37:34,400
Such an important topic. Just, again, to 
remind people why this is so important,  

423
00:37:34,400 --> 00:37:38,120
one of the most common questions founders ask 
is, "Do I have product-market fit? Have I built  

424
00:37:38,120 --> 00:37:42,680
something people want?" That's just an endless 
series of, "I don't know. How do I know? When do  

425
00:37:42,680 --> 00:37:47,600
I know?" And this is telling you in a really 
interesting way. So your advice is this is a  

426
00:37:47,600 --> 00:37:52,120
leading indicator. You don't actually know until 
people actually start using it and whether they  

427
00:37:52,120 --> 00:37:57,960
retain and continue using it. Is there just 
advice on the shift you make from relying  

428
00:37:57,960 --> 00:38:02,040
on the survey to actually looking at retention 
cohorts? Is it just once you have enough data,  

429
00:38:02,040 --> 00:38:05,160
once you have a couple of cohorts, then start 
looking at that? Forget about the survey?

430
00:38:05,160 --> 00:38:12,000
Yeah, but retention cohorts don't give you 
any of the qualitative insights into the why,  

431
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:18,360
so that's why we continue to do the survey. So 
initially I would say if the survey comes back  

432
00:38:18,360 --> 00:38:24,880
and it shows whatever your target number is... 
If you want to be Nubank, it'd be a 50%. Or  

433
00:38:27,640 --> 00:38:31,320
two of the companies I launched, we launched in 
Hungary, and I would say it was the opposite end  

434
00:38:31,320 --> 00:38:40,200
of the spectrum of Brazil, maybe more pessimistic 
than the average culture. And so maybe 30% is good  

435
00:38:40,200 --> 00:38:46,560
enough there, but that ultimately, whatever your 
target is, that you have the signal that says,  

436
00:38:46,560 --> 00:38:51,200
"Okay, we have enough value here. Let's start 
working on growing the business." But while  

437
00:38:51,200 --> 00:38:55,520
you're working on growing the business, I 
would be paying attention to those retention  

438
00:38:55,520 --> 00:39:02,600
cohorts. And if you're churning out all the 
customers who were saying that they'd be  

439
00:39:02,600 --> 00:39:07,800
very disappointed without the product, 
then okay, let's retrench and rethink,  

440
00:39:07,800 --> 00:39:12,840
do we really have product-market fit here and 
what do we need to do to get it if we don't?

441
00:39:12,840 --> 00:39:17,160
Awesome. And speaking of Nubank, if anyone 
wants to see how a company has actually  

442
00:39:17,160 --> 00:39:21,080
operationalized this in the way they operate, 
that there's an episode that we'll link to in  

443
00:39:21,080 --> 00:39:26,840
the show notes where every new product at 
Nubank they build, before they launch it,  

444
00:39:26,840 --> 00:39:32,400
they wait for 50% threshold. For people to 
say 50% of people would be disappointed if  

445
00:39:32,400 --> 00:39:36,520
this product did not exist as they're developing 
it. And only then do they launch it publicly.

446
00:39:36,520 --> 00:39:39,520
Yeah, I think they even do 
it down to the feature level.

447
00:39:39,520 --> 00:39:39,800
Wow.

448
00:39:39,800 --> 00:39:44,400
So if you think about it, how would you 
feel if you can no longer use this feature  

449
00:39:44,400 --> 00:39:48,880
starts to give you, again, the signal, is that 
feature a must-have feature? And if it's not,  

450
00:39:48,880 --> 00:39:55,920
maybe we shouldn't have it. And so yeah, 
I was super excited when I saw how they  

451
00:39:55,920 --> 00:39:59,960
were using the survey and they were 
doing it before I engaged with them.

452
00:39:59,960 --> 00:40:01,740
Oh, wow. That's awesome.

453
00:40:01,740 --> 00:40:05,600
But they were doing it, I think, 
from pretty early on in the business.

454
00:40:05,600 --> 00:40:09,120
The reason they can do this is they have a lot of 
users. They have millions of millions of users,  

455
00:40:09,120 --> 00:40:12,320
so they can ask some small percentage 
of people this question. Because people  

456
00:40:12,320 --> 00:40:14,520
hearing this might be like, "Oh my God, 
how many times am I going to be asked  

457
00:40:14,520 --> 00:40:17,520
this question when I'm using this feature?" 
But they have a lot of users, so it's easier.

458
00:40:17,520 --> 00:40:18,600
Yeah. Yeah.

459
00:40:18,600 --> 00:40:22,880
Okay. Last question, I promise, along these 
lines. Say someone is listening and they're like,  

460
00:40:22,880 --> 00:40:29,600
"Okay. Man, I'm getting 10%, I'm getting 
15%. I don't know what to do to increase  

461
00:40:29,600 --> 00:40:33,680
my product-market fit." You should have just 
a strategy of just dig into the people that  

462
00:40:33,680 --> 00:40:37,640
are very disappointed and see what they 
have to say. But any other advice/what  

463
00:40:38,280 --> 00:40:43,720
do you find often works in helping 
people move from, say, 10% to 40%?

464
00:40:43,720 --> 00:40:49,960
Yeah, so one of the things that's cool about 
almost open-sourcing the survey approach is,  

465
00:40:50,880 --> 00:40:57,080
again, watching how Nubank has evolved their 
usage. But one of the other companies that I think  

466
00:40:57,720 --> 00:41:04,600
used it in an interesting way is Superhuman. And 
I would say that they basically ended up probably  

467
00:41:04,600 --> 00:41:09,320
putting a lot more momentum behind the question 
than it had even before. They posted something  

468
00:41:09,320 --> 00:41:15,280
about how they did it on First Round Capital's 
blog. And what I have always said, and again,  

469
00:41:15,280 --> 00:41:22,000
it's me coming at it from probably initially a 
marketing background, which is I'm taking the  

470
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:29,160
product as a fixed thing, and how do I actually 
figure out how to market and grow this product?  

471
00:41:29,160 --> 00:41:34,960
And product changes are going to take a long 
time, and so what are the variables that I can  

472
00:41:34,960 --> 00:41:42,360
control with a marketing background? So one of 
the things I've always said is just ignore the  

473
00:41:42,360 --> 00:41:47,160
people who say they'd be somewhat disappointed. 
They're telling you it's a nice to have. They're  

474
00:41:47,160 --> 00:41:56,360
as good as gone, so just ignore those guys.
I'll put one piece in the middle there before  

475
00:41:56,360 --> 00:42:01,600
I say what Superhuman did. The reason that 
I say ignore those guys is that if you start  

476
00:42:01,600 --> 00:42:06,480
paying attention to what you somewhat disappointed 
users are telling you, and then you start tweaking  

477
00:42:06,480 --> 00:42:11,440
onboarding and product based on their feedback, 
maybe you're going to dilute it for your must-have  

478
00:42:11,440 --> 00:42:17,640
users. And ultimately, it becomes kind of good 
for everyone but not great for anyone. And so  

479
00:42:17,640 --> 00:42:24,040
that was my fear of trying to read too much into 
the users who say they'd be somewhat disappointed.  

480
00:42:24,040 --> 00:42:28,320
But the Superhuman guys actually found, I think, 
a good way around that where they said, "Okay,  

481
00:42:28,320 --> 00:42:36,000
what is the benefit that my must-have users are 
focused on? And then of the users who say they'd  

482
00:42:36,000 --> 00:42:42,120
be somewhat disappointed, so the nice-to-have 
users, of those users who are also focused on  

483
00:42:42,120 --> 00:42:48,520
that benefit, what do they need in the product 
for it then to become a must-have for them?" 

484
00:42:48,520 --> 00:42:53,920
And so they're staying true to that core 
benefit, but they're trying to essentially  

485
00:42:53,920 --> 00:42:59,360
take those on-the-fence users and moving them 
up. And so I think their way of approaching  

486
00:42:59,360 --> 00:43:04,920
that addressed what my concern was, which is are 
we going to break it for the must-have users?

487
00:43:04,920 --> 00:43:08,760
That's an awesome insight. By the way, 
did Rahul and the team there just do this  

488
00:43:08,760 --> 00:43:11,400
on their own or were you involved 
in any way in this at Superhuman?

489
00:43:11,400 --> 00:43:14,280
No. That's the same thing. Like I 
said, I wasn't initially involved  

490
00:43:14,280 --> 00:43:20,640
with Nubank. I wasn't involved with them. 
We wrote about it in our book in 2017,  

491
00:43:20,640 --> 00:43:27,120
and so I think that I got it out there. But I 
actually teamed up with the Kissmetrics team in  

492
00:43:30,200 --> 00:43:36,440
2012, and essentially published this survey on 
survey.io where we just made it freely available  

493
00:43:36,440 --> 00:43:42,480
for people and a really easy template to prepare 
and send out, and the how-to guide on it. It was  

494
00:43:42,480 --> 00:43:49,240
all just free. Kissmetrics is using it as 
maybe lead gen. And for me, I just wanted  

495
00:43:49,240 --> 00:43:55,240
a way to put something out for the community. 
And so it's been out there for a long time,  

496
00:43:55,240 --> 00:44:01,280
so it's not surprising that different companies 
have found different unique ways to use it.

497
00:44:01,280 --> 00:44:03,280
That's awesome. I think that post 
is one of the most popular in First  

498
00:44:03,280 --> 00:44:05,720
Round. It really had an impact on a lot of people.

499
00:44:05,720 --> 00:44:06,520
Yeah.

500
00:44:06,520 --> 00:44:10,960
So just to repeat, the approach you recommend 
for when you're digging into... I wrote this  

501
00:44:10,960 --> 00:44:15,480
down. When you were talking for how to 
dig into what benefit people are finding,  

502
00:44:15,480 --> 00:44:20,680
your advice is it's basically a follow-up survey 
to the extremely disappointed people asking them  

503
00:44:20,680 --> 00:44:27,040
what is the primary benefit you get? It's an open 
text initially. Then once you get a collection,  

504
00:44:27,720 --> 00:44:31,720
you do it sounds like another survey as 
multiple choice. Here's five benefits-

505
00:44:31,720 --> 00:44:33,240
To a different group of people, to be clear.

506
00:44:33,240 --> 00:44:35,520
Different group. Yeah. Got it. 
Awesome. And then it's like,  

507
00:44:35,520 --> 00:44:38,680
which of these four or five benefits is 
what you're getting out of this product?  

508
00:44:38,680 --> 00:44:41,680
And then the question is, why is 
this benefit important to you?

509
00:44:45,600 --> 00:44:53,440
Eventually the survey.io got closed down, but 
essentially the template that I typically used  

510
00:44:53,440 --> 00:44:58,720
was then moved to PMFsurvey.com. And so you'll see 
some other questions that I have on there as well,  

511
00:44:58,720 --> 00:45:03,360
like what would you use instead if this product 
were no longer available? And that's one of the  

512
00:45:03,360 --> 00:45:07,120
interesting things is you start to see people 
who say they'd be somewhat disappointed,  

513
00:45:07,120 --> 00:45:11,920
usually, they're focused on a commodity 
use case and they know an easy alternative  

514
00:45:11,920 --> 00:45:18,360
to switch to. So to be a must-have, it 
needs to be both valuable and unique.

515
00:45:18,360 --> 00:45:21,680
Okay. Anything else on this 
topic of the Sean Ellis task  

516
00:45:21,680 --> 00:45:24,840
product-market fit test before we 
move on to growth strategy advice?

517
00:45:24,840 --> 00:45:26,480
No, I think that's it.

518
00:45:26,480 --> 00:45:29,600
I think we did almost an hour on that 
one topic, which I love because I feel  

519
00:45:29,600 --> 00:45:33,920
like this is such a powerful tool that I 
think people sort of know and have used,  

520
00:45:33,920 --> 00:45:38,400
but I think there's a lot of opportunity to 
use it more effectively. And all the stuff  

521
00:45:38,400 --> 00:45:43,200
you pointed out about it's not just you have this 
threshold goal, let's move, let's grow. It's like,  

522
00:45:43,200 --> 00:45:47,720
this is how you figure out how to make it better 
and better and grow faster and faster. And it's  

523
00:45:47,720 --> 00:45:52,000
actually a good segue to talking about growth.
Even though you coined the term growth hacking,  

524
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:56,680
you spend most of your time on the opposite, 
essentially, which is helping companies figure  

525
00:45:56,680 --> 00:46:00,440
out sustainable growth strategies, not just 
a bunch of hacks to grow for a little bit and  

526
00:46:00,440 --> 00:46:06,440
then disappear. And from what I've seen, it's 
all rooted in this idea of product-market fit  

527
00:46:06,440 --> 00:46:10,800
and what helps you find product-market fit, and 
I imagine many of the stuff we've talked about.

528
00:46:10,800 --> 00:46:15,360
Yeah. Just one quick interjection there 
is that when I coined growth hacking,  

529
00:46:15,360 --> 00:46:21,760
I did not think of it as a bunch of one-off hacks. 
What I thought of it was what's more about what is  

530
00:46:21,760 --> 00:46:26,800
the way to ultimately drive sustainable 
growth? But it's, over time, maybe more  

531
00:46:27,320 --> 00:46:30,480
interpreted the way you described 
it, but just to jump in and say that.

532
00:46:30,480 --> 00:46:34,520
That's a really good clarification, so how did 
you actually initially frame it when you first-

533
00:46:34,520 --> 00:46:41,920
Yeah, I just said it's about looking at every 
single thing that you're doing and scrutinizing  

534
00:46:41,920 --> 00:46:48,760
its impact on growth in the business. And 
particularly, I think most marketers, when I first  

535
00:46:48,760 --> 00:46:54,320
moved to Silicon Valley, most CEOs who were asking 
me to help their companies, they were saying,  

536
00:46:54,320 --> 00:46:59,760
"We need help with awareness-building," and I'm 
getting introductions from top VCs. And so, so  

537
00:46:59,760 --> 00:47:08,400
much of, I think, the way people were approaching 
growth was marketing textbook how to approach it.  

538
00:47:08,400 --> 00:47:13,760
And startups just don't have the luxury to do all 
of those things, and so you got to really focus on  

539
00:47:13,760 --> 00:47:18,800
how do I acquire customers to an experience that's 
going to make them keep using this product? And  

540
00:47:18,800 --> 00:47:24,480
so maybe I picked the wrong term in calling it 
growth hacking, but I think it at least opened  

541
00:47:24,480 --> 00:47:28,760
the conversation to getting more people thinking 
about maybe we should be thinking about growth in  

542
00:47:28,760 --> 00:47:33,640
a different way than as it's traditionally 
taught in marketing courses in school.

543
00:47:33,640 --> 00:47:36,080
Is there another term you think you should 
have used? Do you always think back,  

544
00:47:36,080 --> 00:47:38,920
I should have called it this? Is there 
anything that you've had in your mind?

545
00:47:38,920 --> 00:47:45,240
I don't. I think sometimes having something 
that's a little divisive is almost better  

546
00:47:45,240 --> 00:47:53,680
because it's too easy to just go completely 
unnoticed. But I was trying to put a name  

547
00:47:53,680 --> 00:47:59,320
on not just how I was approaching growth, but 
seeing Facebook obviously had a very different  

548
00:47:59,320 --> 00:48:04,000
approach to growth than most companies. 
LinkedIn, Twitter, there was a handful  

549
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:07,560
of companies that were approaching it in the 
same way I had previously been approaching it,  

550
00:48:07,560 --> 00:48:14,360
and I just thought this thing needs a name. And so 
I sat down with a couple of friends, came up with  

551
00:48:14,360 --> 00:48:23,040
a name and it stuck. But yeah, obviously from day 
one it was pretty divisive with different groups.

552
00:48:23,040 --> 00:48:27,720
That's a fun story. Thanks for sharing that.
Okay, so talking about growth and helping  

553
00:48:27,720 --> 00:48:34,360
companies figure out how to grow. Say you go 
to a company, they're getting 42% on the Sean  

554
00:48:34,360 --> 00:48:38,560
Ellis test, and they're like, "Okay, cool, let's 
start thinking about growth." What's your first  

555
00:48:38,560 --> 00:48:41,960
piece of advice to them to start when they're 
thinking about growth? And then just broadly,  

556
00:48:41,960 --> 00:48:45,480
how do you approach helping 
them figure out how to grow?

557
00:48:45,480 --> 00:48:51,560
Ultimately, it's about trying to get as many of 
the right people to that same state that we just  

558
00:48:51,560 --> 00:48:57,120
talked about with the must-have users, so trying 
to get as many people to experience the product  

559
00:48:57,120 --> 00:49:00,960
in a way where they'd be very disappointed 
if they could no longer use the product.  

560
00:49:00,960 --> 00:49:07,160
And so that's not just acquisition, which is 
how most companies think about... Initially,  

561
00:49:07,160 --> 00:49:12,200
it was awareness then maybe the more developed 
way was, oh, let's at least focus on profitable  

562
00:49:12,200 --> 00:49:23,400
acquisition. But in my experience, the hardest 
part really sits inside the product team, so how  

563
00:49:23,400 --> 00:49:28,600
do you shape that first user experience so they 
actually use it in the right way and it's not so  

564
00:49:28,600 --> 00:49:34,200
difficult that they give up? And that ultimately, 
we understand what makes it a must-have product.  

565
00:49:34,200 --> 00:49:40,200
And then what we're trying to do is build 
a... Yeah, it sounds kind of theoretical here,  

566
00:49:40,200 --> 00:49:45,800
but I can go into the details on how, but 
build a flywheel around that must-have value. 

567
00:49:45,800 --> 00:49:55,200
So step one would be understand it. Step two for 
me is then figure out a metric that essentially  

568
00:49:55,200 --> 00:50:02,880
captures units of that value being delivered. And 
so when I think about a north star metric, that's  

569
00:50:02,880 --> 00:50:11,840
what I'm thinking about is something that reflects 
how many people are coming in and experiencing  

570
00:50:11,840 --> 00:50:16,360
that product-market fit experience, whatever 
that is. And it's not just me telling them,  

571
00:50:16,360 --> 00:50:21,680
"Here's what your north star metric should be." 
It's that ultimately the team needs to decide that  

572
00:50:21,680 --> 00:50:29,920
together. And then really just diagramming, what 
are all of the different ways that we can grow  

573
00:50:29,920 --> 00:50:35,200
that north star metric? So that's where you start 
to actually build, I call it a value delivery  

574
00:50:35,200 --> 00:50:42,520
engine, but it's what does our onboarding look 
like? What's that aha moment? That activation?  

575
00:50:42,520 --> 00:50:47,720
What does the engagement loop look like? Is there 
any referral? Try to capture it as it is today. 

576
00:50:47,720 --> 00:50:53,560
And then, from there, thinking about where are the 
biggest opportunities for improvement, so those  

577
00:50:53,560 --> 00:50:59,280
high-leverage opportunities, and then ultimately 
starting to run experiments against those  

578
00:50:59,280 --> 00:51:03,240
opportunities. Generally, I think I touched on it 
a little bit earlier, but generally the sequence  

579
00:51:03,240 --> 00:51:10,160
that I like to do is start with activation because 
that one's just so critical and it's easy to get  

580
00:51:10,160 --> 00:51:16,520
lost in between, especially for an early product. 
The product team's so focused on the roadmap.  

581
00:51:16,520 --> 00:51:21,480
We're two features away from not even needing 
marketing anymore. This thing's going to take off.  

582
00:51:21,480 --> 00:51:27,320
And then a marketing team so focused on bringing 
new people in, but how do you get those new people  

583
00:51:27,320 --> 00:51:33,080
to a great first experience falls through the 
cracks a lot of times. So a lot of focus on  

584
00:51:33,080 --> 00:51:41,720
activation and then engagement and referral 
and getting the revenue model right. And then  

585
00:51:41,720 --> 00:51:49,160
once each of those pieces are working well, then 
starting to really obsess on the channel side. 

586
00:51:49,160 --> 00:51:53,880
One thing that I'll say. When I go in 
and directly am involved with a company  

587
00:51:53,880 --> 00:52:01,160
on the acquisition side, I am thinking about my 
hypotheses on the acquisition pretty early on,  

588
00:52:01,160 --> 00:52:06,920
because if I go into it and I have no 
idea how we'll acquire those customers,  

589
00:52:06,920 --> 00:52:11,400
I'm not real confident I'll figure it out when I'm 
there. So I want to have two or three things that  

590
00:52:11,400 --> 00:52:19,440
seem pretty viable as ways to profitably acquire 
customers, and knowing that once I get deep into  

591
00:52:19,440 --> 00:52:25,320
it, I'll probably come up with one or two more 
and I've got five, one of them's likely to work.  

592
00:52:25,320 --> 00:52:29,720
But I don't want to just be under the pressure 
of having to come up with that once I come in,  

593
00:52:29,720 --> 00:52:36,760
if I don't at least see an angle from that 
before I get involved with the company.

594
00:52:36,760 --> 00:52:40,400
What I'm hearing is when you come into 
a company and they're asking, "Sean,  

595
00:52:40,400 --> 00:52:44,800
how do we figure out how to grow this thing?" you 
actually focus first on activation onboarding,  

596
00:52:44,800 --> 00:52:48,440
and we're going to talk about all these things. 
Then, after that, basically these are priority  

597
00:52:48,440 --> 00:52:54,160
order for you. Then it's flywheel engagement 
referral stuff to see if there's a way to drive  

598
00:52:54,160 --> 00:52:59,360
that. Then revenue. How do we make money with 
this and how do we make sure we're doing this  

599
00:52:59,360 --> 00:53:05,080
profitably? And only then do you start to 
go big on acquisition top-of-funnel growth.

600
00:53:05,080 --> 00:53:09,160
Yeah. I may need to do some acquisition stuff 
before just to bring enough flow-through,  

601
00:53:09,160 --> 00:53:14,400
but I'm not obsessing on how scalable is this. 
It's just like, yeah, let's get enough people  

602
00:53:14,400 --> 00:53:20,920
coming through that we can start to take the slack 
out. Part of it comes down to that the acquisition  

603
00:53:20,920 --> 00:53:26,680
side is so competitive now that if you're not 
really efficient at converting and retaining  

604
00:53:26,680 --> 00:53:32,960
and monetizing customers, you can't find scalable, 
profitable customer acquisition channels.

605
00:53:32,960 --> 00:53:36,480
This is fascinating because I think a 
lot of people probably do the opposite.  

606
00:53:36,480 --> 00:53:39,400
Start driving a bunch of growth to a 
product, then we'll fix onboarding,  

607
00:53:39,400 --> 00:53:43,120
then we'll figure out how we're making 
money, and referrals comes along there.  

608
00:53:43,120 --> 00:53:47,960
So I think this is really important for people 
to hear. So again, the reason you invest first  

609
00:53:47,960 --> 00:53:53,680
and focus a lot on onboarding/getting people 
activated is because that is very correlated  

610
00:53:53,680 --> 00:53:58,520
to retention and this must-have customer, 
this, "I'll be very disappointed," customer.

611
00:53:58,520 --> 00:54:04,080
Yeah. And they're at highest risk 
of losing them at that point. They-

612
00:54:04,080 --> 00:54:05,560
They're at highest risk of losing them at that 
point. They're probably a little skeptical about  

613
00:54:05,560 --> 00:54:11,480
a promise that you put out there, but they're 
intrigued enough to want to use it. But until  

614
00:54:11,480 --> 00:54:17,480
you get them to that must-have experience, until 
you kind of get them to that aha moment, they're  

615
00:54:17,480 --> 00:54:21,880
at their high risk of being lost. And so a lot of 
people focus on, "Well, I better get their email  

616
00:54:21,880 --> 00:54:27,040
address or their phone number." But then you're 
essentially having to reacquire them at that  

617
00:54:27,040 --> 00:54:36,000
point. So to me, if you can collapse that time 
to value, I can give you a couple of incredible  

618
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:41,520
examples of when we [inaudible 00:54:38]
So at LogMeIn, when we initially tried to  

619
00:54:41,520 --> 00:54:47,440
grow the business, I was stuck at being able to 
spend... I couldn't spend more than $10,000 per  

620
00:54:47,440 --> 00:54:56,080
month profitably trying to grow the business. And 
then I dug into the data and I saw that 95% of the  

621
00:54:56,080 --> 00:55:04,400
people signing up for LogMeIn. So LogMeIn, at the 
time free remote access for your computer. And so  

622
00:55:04,400 --> 00:55:09,600
you install software and you can control it from 
any other computer. So 95% of the people signing  

623
00:55:09,600 --> 00:55:16,240
up never once did a remote control session. 
And so not surprisingly, then I had to get my  

624
00:55:16,240 --> 00:55:22,400
monetization off the 5% who did that was really 
limiting my ability to find channels that worked. 

625
00:55:24,200 --> 00:55:30,760
Credit our CEO with this, that I shared the data 
with him and he basically told the product team,  

626
00:55:30,760 --> 00:55:36,480
"We are putting a complete freeze on the product 
development roadmap." So every single person from  

627
00:55:36,480 --> 00:55:43,560
product, engineering, design and then also said 
to me, "Stop trying to find new channels." The  

628
00:55:43,560 --> 00:55:49,040
three of us on the marketing side are all going 
to focus on improving the signup to usage rate.  

629
00:55:49,040 --> 00:55:54,680
And so in three months, we improve the signup to 
usage rate by a thousand percent. So we went from  

630
00:55:54,680 --> 00:56:01,280
only 5% of people using the product to 50%. 
I went back, tried the exact same channels  

631
00:56:01,280 --> 00:56:07,440
that previously only scaled to $10,000 a month.
Now they scaled to a million dollars a month with  

632
00:56:07,440 --> 00:56:12,120
