a lot of it comes down to not the things you try, 
but how you deeply understand the problem that's  

651
00:57:58,600 --> 00:58:05,040
preventing someone from using your product 
effectively. And so I'll just give you one  

652
00:58:05,040 --> 00:58:11,960
example. We had one channel after we made a lot 
of these changes and had already driven a ton of  

653
00:58:11,960 --> 00:58:20,680
improvement in the LogMeIn onboarding. We found 
a demand generation channel that was really cheap  

654
00:58:20,680 --> 00:58:26,360
and the economics looked great, but at just 
the download step we had a 90% drop off rate. 

655
00:58:26,360 --> 00:58:34,560
And so we A/B tested a bunch of different things 
there to try to improve that conversion rate, and  

656
00:58:34,560 --> 00:58:41,240
then finally 10 plus tests, not able to improve 
it. Finally, someone said, "When these people are  

657
00:58:41,240 --> 00:58:46,640
registering. Why don't we just ask them why they 
signed up and didn't download the software?" And  

658
00:58:46,640 --> 00:58:51,960
so we didn't want to do it in too kind of a creepy 
way. So we made it look like a note coming from  

659
00:58:51,960 --> 00:59:00,240
customer service. This channel was sending 200,000 
people a day, so 20,000 people were converting to  

660
00:59:00,240 --> 00:59:07,240
registering. So we had essentially 20,000 people 
we could email and then 18,000 of them who didn't  

661
00:59:07,240 --> 00:59:11,520
download. And so we just asked, "Hey, notice 
you haven't had a chance to use the product yet. 

662
00:59:11,520 --> 00:59:16,720
It looked like it was coming from customer 
support. What happened?" And the answer we  

663
00:59:16,720 --> 00:59:22,240
got back and not a formal survey was, "Oh, this 
seemed too good to be true. I didn't believe this  

664
00:59:22,240 --> 00:59:29,960
was free." I mentioned to you we were one of the 
first freemium SaaS products out there. And so  

665
00:59:29,960 --> 00:59:35,040
people were skeptical, especially in a demand 
gen channel where they hadn't seen a radio or  

666
00:59:35,040 --> 00:59:39,680
a TV advertisement from our competitor who was 
a premium only product. These were people who  

667
00:59:39,680 --> 00:59:46,800
were discovering the category for the first time 
they were getting there. Once we articulated what  

668
00:59:46,800 --> 00:59:53,840
the problem was, our next test gave us a 300% 
improvement in the download rate, which was... 

669
00:59:53,840 --> 00:59:58,960
We gave them a choice, download a trial of 
the paid version or download the free version,  

670
00:59:58,960 --> 01:00:03,200
put a big graphical check mark next to the free 
version. But when they saw we had a business  

671
01:00:03,200 --> 01:00:08,680
model and a trial of a paid version, the free 
version was credible. And so that essentially  

672
01:00:08,680 --> 01:00:14,520
made that channel work for us. So I think again, 
it's that combination of qualitative research,  

673
01:00:14,520 --> 01:00:19,080
looking at how others did it. We had this theory, 
our previous company had been a game company that  

674
01:00:19,080 --> 01:00:24,720
didn't require a download. So initially we had 
this theory that maybe just downloadable software  

675
01:00:24,720 --> 01:00:31,560
can't be in the millions of new customers a 
month and so we're being unrealistic here. 

676
01:00:31,560 --> 01:00:34,920
But then we were like, "Are there any 
counter examples to that"? And no,  

677
01:00:34,920 --> 01:00:40,040
the instant messengers are downloadable and 
they have hundreds of millions of customers,  

678
01:00:40,040 --> 01:00:44,920
so let's study their download and install 
process and see if we have any ideas that  

679
01:00:44,920 --> 01:00:49,600
we could borrow from that. So again, some 
inspiration, tried some of those things,  

680
01:00:49,600 --> 01:00:55,040
it was a combination of just trying a bunch 
of different stuff that ultimately led to,  

681
01:00:55,600 --> 01:01:00,560
I wouldn't say there was one big 
gain, it was a bunch of small gains.

682
01:01:00,560 --> 01:01:04,880
Awesome. So a few things for people to try 
if they're like, "Hey, how do I improve my  

683
01:01:04,880 --> 01:01:10,320
activation rate? How do I improve my conversion 
rate?" Just drill further into what is stopping  

684
01:01:10,320 --> 01:01:15,280
people from progressing. Ask them, "Why did you 
bounce here? What did you think this was going  

685
01:01:15,280 --> 01:01:18,840
to be? Why didn't you end up using this?" 
Look for inspiration from other products,  

686
01:01:18,840 --> 01:01:23,080
I think people probably already know that. You 
talked about earlier this idea of the positioning,  

687
01:01:23,080 --> 01:01:27,600
having a big impact of just figuring out.
They want an antivirus software. Let's make  

688
01:01:27,600 --> 01:01:31,080
that very clear. "Hey we've got the best 
antivirus software, that's what we're here  

689
01:01:31,080 --> 01:01:36,480
for." So there's probably just messaging 
that you find works a lot of times, right?

690
01:01:36,480 --> 01:01:41,880
I mean your two big levers on driving a 
conversion are increase desire, reduce  

691
01:01:41,880 --> 01:01:49,880
friction. And so you definitely want to increase 
the right desire. Sometimes it can also just be  

692
01:01:49,880 --> 01:01:54,760
reminding people along the way of what benefits 
you're going to get. In the case of LogmeIn,  

693
01:01:54,760 --> 01:02:01,040
it was probably the most complicated funnel I've 
ever seen because you couldn't even get to the  

694
01:02:01,040 --> 01:02:07,120
aha moment while you're sitting in front of the 
computer. You had to actually go to a different  

695
01:02:07,120 --> 01:02:11,800
computer and to use the service to remote 
control the computer you're in front of. 

696
01:02:11,800 --> 01:02:17,080
So it's not surprising that there was so many 
steps where we could lose people, but we just  

697
01:02:17,080 --> 01:02:22,680
weren't that intentional about designing each 
of those steps initially. And it wasn't until  

698
01:02:22,680 --> 01:02:28,200
we thought through why would we lose someone at 
this step and studying the data, which steps were  

699
01:02:28,200 --> 01:02:33,600
we losing the most people at? Then deeply trying 
to contextualize why are we losing them there,  

700
01:02:33,600 --> 01:02:38,080
coming up with a set of tests that we want to run 
and then having a good way of deciding which one  

701
01:02:38,080 --> 01:02:45,640
to test first and ultimately focusing the tests 
on the areas where we're losing the most people.

702
01:02:45,640 --> 01:02:48,480
The other element of this is coming up 
with an activation metric and aligning  

703
01:02:48,480 --> 01:02:53,800
on here's what we consider so activated. I 
know this is very dependent on the product,  

704
01:02:53,800 --> 01:02:58,440
but any advice or heuristic for how to help 
people decide this is our activated user.

705
01:02:58,440 --> 01:03:04,120
I tend to start qualitatively. So just like when 
do I think they've had a good enough experience  

706
01:03:04,120 --> 01:03:10,840
with the product to really know it? And so in 
the case of LogMeIn, it was pretty easy. If they  

707
01:03:10,840 --> 01:03:16,960
didn't do a remote control session, they didn't 
use the product. There was no value along the way  

708
01:03:16,960 --> 01:03:22,840
there. And then at least try to see if there's a 
correlation to long-term retention of doing that.  

709
01:03:22,840 --> 01:03:28,560
Causation is you need to do some experimentation 
to prove causation. At the very least, I want to  

710
01:03:28,560 --> 01:03:36,720
see that correlation, but if I start with two 
or three ideas of what it might be and then  

711
01:03:36,720 --> 01:03:43,040
go and study the data, that can help you focus.
But again, I don't think there's necessarily one  

712
01:03:43,040 --> 01:03:47,720
exact right answer of what is that aha moment. 
There might be two or three different things.  

713
01:03:47,720 --> 01:03:53,320
I think it's that intentionality about picking 
something that's experience-based and saying,  

714
01:03:53,320 --> 01:03:58,840
"What is a likely experience that someone's going 
to get a good enough taste of this product?" And  

715
01:03:58,840 --> 01:04:05,200
then I do see some companies that are like, "Well, 
the activation moment should be, they've used it a  

716
01:04:05,200 --> 01:04:12,400
hundred times." That's going to correlate to 
long-term retention, but it's just not very  

717
01:04:12,400 --> 01:04:18,240
actionable. It's so far down the user experience.
So ideally if there's a way that I could get them  

718
01:04:18,240 --> 01:04:23,760
there in the first session, in the first day, 
that's great. And so it's sort of something  

719
01:04:23,760 --> 01:04:28,960
that's value that can be experienced super 
early. To give you an example from the first  

720
01:04:28,960 --> 01:04:34,560
company I worked on was a game company, where 
I actually flipped it and basically instead  

721
01:04:34,560 --> 01:04:39,760
of making a traditional funnel where they 
could play our games after they signed up,  

722
01:04:39,760 --> 01:04:48,120
I made our games the advertisements. So basically 
we syndicated our games to 40,000 websites. 

723
01:04:48,120 --> 01:04:54,160
They started gameplay experience on the other 
website, then they would get a message that  

724
01:04:54,160 --> 01:05:01,240
they now have a qualifying score and if they 
register, they'll be in the drawing for the  

725
01:05:01,240 --> 01:05:07,480
weekly cash prize and then we could pull them into 
